Jing Jie [荊芥; pinyin: Jīng Jiè]. 

Chinese name: 荊芥 (Jīng Jiè). Japanese Kampo name: Keigai (荊芥). Also known classically by the alternate name Jiǎ Sū [假蘇, 'false perilla']. 

Classical category: Middle Herb [中品, zhōng pǐn] in the Shennong Bencaojing tripartite classification. 

Five Flavors [五味, wǔ wèi]: Acrid [辛, xīn]. 
Four Natures [四氣, sì qì]: Warm [溫, wēn]. 
Channel Tropism [歸經, guī jīng]: Lung [肺], Liver [肝]. (Channel assignments elaborated in post-classical Kampo and Song–Jin–Yuan commentary; not fully systematized in the original Shennong Bencaojing.) 

Classical indications (Shennong Bencaojing, c.200 CE): 
— Governs [主] alternating cold and heat [寒熱, hán rè]; 
— Scrofulous sores and rat-fistula [鼠瘻, shǔ lòu]; 
— Scrofula with ulceration [瘰癧生瘡, luǒ lì shēng chuāng]; 
— Breaks up and disperses accumulations and bound qi [破結聚氣, pò jié jù qì]; 
— Moves and descends static blood [下瘀血, xià yū xuè]; 
— Eliminates damp painful obstruction [除濕痹, chú shī bì]. 
— Habitat recorded as river valleys and marshlands [生川澤]. 

Expanded therapeutic actions (Kampo and subsequent classical elaboration): 
In Japanese Kampo medicine (reflecting Tao Hongjing, Li Shizhen's Bencao Gangmu, and Kampo systematization), Jing Jie is principally classified as an exterior-releasing herb that dispels wind [祛風解表, qū fēng jiě biǎo], both wind-cold and wind-heat, making it notably neutral among warming acrid herbs. Key elaborated actions include: 
— Releasing the exterior and dispersing wind [解表散風]; 
— Venting rashes and resolving toxin [透疹解毒, tòu zhěn jiě dú] — a primary classical indication for measles, urticaria, and early-stage rashes that have not fully surfaced; 
— Stopping bleeding [止血, zhǐ xuè] — especially when the herb or its charred preparation [荊芥炭, Jīng Jiè Tàn] is used for uterine bleeding, bloody stool, and epistaxis; 
— Relieving throat disorders with wind toxin [利咽]; 
— In Kampo, emphasized for skin diseases, itching, and early febrile disorders with surface constraint. 

Notable classical formulas featuring Jing Jie: 
— Jing Fang Baidu San [荊防敗毒散]: Jing Jie + Fang Feng for wind-cold with dampness, widely used in Kampo for skin eruptions and febrile illness; 
— Xiaofeng San [消風散]: dispels wind and clears heat, used for urticaria and eczema; 
— Fang Feng Tong Sheng San [防風通聖散]: classical Kampo compound formula incorporating Jing Jie for exterior-interior simultaneous release; 
— Jing Jie Lian Qiao Tang [荊芥連翹湯]: prominent in Kampo dermatology for inflammatory skin conditions and sinusitis. 

Preparation notes: Used unprepared [生用] for exterior-releasing and rash-venting; charred [炒炭] for hemostatic applications. Contraindicated in cases of already-expressed rashes or deficiency patterns without exterior constraint.

Di Fu Zi [Ground-Skin Seed / Kochia fruit], flavor: bitter [ku]; nature: cold [han]. Classical category: Superior Herb [shang pin].

Primary actions according to the Shennong Bencaojing: Governs [zhu] heat in the Bladder [pangguang re]; promotes urination [li xiao bian]; supplements the Center [bu zhong] and augments Essence-Qi [yi jing qi]. Taken over a long period [jiu fu], it sharpens hearing and brightens vision [er mu cong ming], lightens the body [qing shen], and confers resistance to aging [nai lao]. Also known by the alternate name Di Kui [地葵, 'Ground Mallow']. Found growing in flat marshlands and open fields.

Five Flavors [wu wei]: Bitter [ku].
Four Natures [si qi]: Cold [han].
Channel Tropism [gui jing] (as elaborated in later classical and Kampo tradition): Bladder [pangguang jing]; Kidney [shen jing].

Japanese Kampo name: Jifushi [地膚子, じふし].

Expanded therapeutic profile (post-Shennong elaboration through Tang, Song, and Kampo traditions):
— Clears Damp-Heat [qing shi re] from the lower burner [xia jiao], particularly the Bladder;
— Promotes urination and relieves lin syndrome [li xiao bian, zhi lin zheng]: dysuria, turbid urine, scanty and painful urination associated with damp-heat accumulation;
— Dispels Wind and stops itching [qu feng zhi yang]: used topically and internally for skin conditions characterized by damp-heat — urticaria [feng zhen], eczema [shi zhen], genital pruritus [yin yang], and generalized pruritus;
— Clears Heat and resolves toxicity [qing re jie du] in dermatological applications.

Key classical formulas:
— Di Fu Zi Tang [地膚子湯] (Qian Jin Yao Fang /备急千金要方, Sun Simiao, c.652 CE): addresses difficult urination and damp-heat lin syndrome;
— Combined with Bai Xian Pi [白鮮皮], She Chuang Zi [蛇床子], and Ku Shen [苦參] in topical washes for pruritic skin conditions;
— Appears in various Kampo formulations for urinary tract irritation and dermatitis with a damp-heat pattern.

Preparation: Decocted [jian] for internal use, typically 9–15 g; also used as an external wash [xi] decocted in water for itching and skin eruptions. Seeds are harvested in autumn when the fruiting spike is mature.
